<SECOND>PM-End of Tolls,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tolls End in Jacksonville Amid Demolition, Fireworks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazouri </PERSON>, at the controls of a crane wielding a wrecking ball, officially marked the end of 36 years of toll bridges in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> by helping demolish several toll booths. After collecting some $ 370 million in tolls from 1.5 billion motorists, the tolls were removed Friday from four local bridges and a four-lane expressway. `` We have taken a quantum leap forward in improving the quality of life for our city. Today is like New Year's, Christmas and the Fourth of July rolled into one,'' <PERSON> Hazouri </PERSON> said at ceremonies at the <LOCATION> Mathews </LOCATION> bridge, which opened in 1953. Moments earlier signs were unveiled on the <LOCATION> Mathews </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> toll plazas reading, `` No Tolls, Pass Thru.'' At the same time, the tolls also ended on the <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Trout </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> bridges and on <LOCATION> Butler </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boulevard </LOCATION>, a four-lane expressway linking <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 95 </ORGANIZATION> to the beach. There was a festive party atmosphere on the <LOCATION> Mathews </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>, with crowds cheering, horns honking and the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Band </LOCATION> playing. Fireworks were ignited on Quarantine Island in the middle of the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. The mayor and <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Jacksonville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, climbed aboard a large yellow crane, and with the help of a crane operator, toppled several toll booths. In a large front-page headline, The <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Union </ORGANIZATION> proclaimed Friday, `` Un-tolled joy: KEEP THE CHANGE.'' The removal of the tolls was made possible by the passage in March 1988 of a half-cent city sales tax. In addition to removing tolls on existing bridges, the new <LOCATION> Dames </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> opened toll-free earlier this year. The removal of the tolls cames 18 months after the voters approved the concept. The wait was necessary to convince state officials that the sales tax revenue would generate sufficient funds to cover the refinancing of $ 200 million in outstanding toll-revenue bonds issued in 1963, 1977 and 1985.
