<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Juror Is Dismissed For Sleeping In Night Stalker Deliberations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 13th day of jury deliberations in the `` Night Stalker'' trial was interrupted Friday when the judge dismissed a juror for sleeping and ordered the panel to start all over again. An alternate juror was chosen to replace the sleeping juror in the complex case involving 13 murders and 30 felonies committed during the summer of l985. Jurors heard six months of testimony after six months of jury selection. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>, a 29-year-old drifter from <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, is accused of being the devil-worshipping `` Night Stalker'' who raped, murdered and robbed victims in a rampage that terrified <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON> said he and defense lawyer <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> were summoned Friday to the courtroom of <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Tynan </PERSON> after the jury foreman sent a note saying that one juror had been seen sleeping at the deliberation table. <PERSON> Tynan </PERSON> interviewed the foreman who said two other jurors had reported seeing the man in question nodding off and snoring in the deliberation room. After a brief discussion with attorneys, <PERSON> Tynan </PERSON> summoned the juror and told him he was being dismissed for sleeping. The juror did not protest. The judge then brought the entire panel into the courtroom. He told them not to speculate on why the juror was being dismissed and instructed them to begin their talks anew with the alternate filling the dismissed juror's place. <PERSON> Halpin </PERSON> said it was impossible to tell how long it would take now for the jury to reach a unanimous decision on the 43 counts involved. Earlier this week, the jury returned to the courtroom to ask for a repeat of testimony involving <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>' dental problems. It was the first time they had asked for testimony to be read back since they began deliberating July 26.
