<HEAD>Police Nab Suspected Dealer Who Calls 911 for Information</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HATTIESBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A suspected crack dealer curious about a police round-up called a 911 emergency number to ask if authorities were looking for him. When he hung up, he had his answer _ officers were at his door. Police said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Mays </PERSON>, 33, of <LOCATION> Forrest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> telephoned the police emergency line on Thursday night to ask about a report he heard on the street _ a grand jury had indicted 101 people suspected of dealing crack and police were looking for them. A computerized system flashed the address from which <PERSON> Mays </PERSON> was telephoning, and officers sped to the house and arrested him, a sheriff's office spokesman said. The indictments were issued Thursday, and by Friday afternoon officers had arrested more than 50 people accused of selling crack to undercover agents working with the <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Narcotics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. District Attorney <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> said arraignments would be held Aug. 25. The investigation began early this year, authorities said.
