<HEAD>Justice Department Says Disclosure Hurt Bloch Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is hardening its assessment of the damage done by public disclosure to its investigation of suspected <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> spy <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said flatly Friday that the July 21 disclosure that the 54-year-old <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat was under investigation had compromised the investigation. `` There is no doubt that the premature disclosure of that case, the premature disclosure that there was an ongoing investigation, did compromise the investigation,'' <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said. He did n't explain how the investigation had been compromised. However, <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON>'s assessment was much stronger than one he delivered July 31 when asked about the impact of unprecedented publicity on an espionage investigation that so far has produced no criminal charges. He said then that `` the premature disclosure may have had an adverse impact on the development of new evidence in the case.'' The investigation of <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, the No. 2 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> for much of the decade, was disclosed July 21 by <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. `` The differences in the statements reflects a different view, based on how people in the department see the situation today,'' <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said Friday when asked about the contrast between his two assessments. He acknowledged the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> opposed the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to issue a statement after the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> broadcast that essentially confirmed the accuracy of the report. The television report and a series of disclosures have produced what <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> called `` the circus going on out there'' of reporters and <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents tailing <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> each day on daily excursions from his apartment. On Thursday, <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> acknowledged the department does n't have an espionage case against <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, who was placed on paid leave by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Asked why there were no charges despite continuous <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> surveillance of <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said: `` The department does not bring charges unless it believes it has sufficient evidence to convince a jury beyond a reasonable doubt that a person is guilty of violating the law.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> has been conducting a round-the-clock surveillance of <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> to prevent him from leaving the country while investigators try to find evidence to charge him with espionage. <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> refused to comment when asked if the department had evidence that it was unwilling to disclose in court for fear of hurting counterintelligence operations. <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, meantime, led reporters and photographers on a Friday afternoon shopping excursion to a suburban supermarket. About 1 p.m., <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> announced he was about to leave his apartment. Two hours later, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> finally emerged, driving his light-blue <ORGANIZATION> Mercedez-Benz </ORGANIZATION>. He invited two television crews to ride along while he went on errands. Followed by a 20-car caravan of reporters, TV crews and <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> drove to a shopping center in nearby <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, where he shopped at a supermarket and a bookstore. The supermarket manager asked the TV crews to leave the store after a cameraman who was backpeddling to film <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> buying groceries knocked over an elderly woman, who cut her hand on the floor.
