 The <ORGANIZATION> Guardian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angels </ORGANIZATION> intend to set up a subway patrol in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> despite opposition from local officials, one of the group's leaders says. <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Sliwa </PERSON> completed a five-day tour of the subway system on Friday and told reporters she would return in September to recruit and train French Guardian Angels. `` We are really needed here,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Sliwa </PERSON>, who wore the red beret and white T-shirt that the New York-based group has adopted as a uniform. The <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> transit authority and police unions have said they oppose a Guardian Angel patrol. `` We are completely opposed to those who act as a militia or other police force,'' said a statement issued Monday by the transit authority. Ms. <PERSON> Sliwa </PERSON> said she had since met with police and transit authority officials and, while not getting their approval, plans to go ahead with setting up a subway patrol. `` We are not a militia,'' she said. She said the Guardian Angels, founded in 1979, patrol subways in 44 American cities, as well as in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>.
