<SECOND>PM-North Sentence,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Sentence Could Have Been Harsher Under Federal Guidelines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A legal publication says <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> could have been sentenced to more than 4 -LCB- years in prison if federal sentencing guidelines had been applied to his Iran-Contra conviction. However, the guidelines that recommend ranges of possible sentences to judges were n't applied in the North case because they cover only federal crimes committed after Nov. 1, 1987. The editors of the Federal Sentencing Reporter, a non-profit publication circulated among federal judges, probation officers, law professors and lawyers, concluded <PERSON> North </PERSON> could have been sentenced under the guidelines to 21 to 57 months in prison. North was convicted of aiding and abetting obstruction of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, destroying government documents and accepting an illegal gratuity while working at the White House in 1986. He was fined, put on probation and ordered to do community service _ but was sentenced to no jail time. North began his community service work this week. The ranges `` sketch possible avenues guideline sentencing might have taken,'' <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. Freed of <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> said in their analysis. If <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s had been a guidelines case, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> still could have imposed no jail time but prosecutors would have been able to appeal. Under the guidelines, `` there is a degree of flexibility, but the challenge for the judge is to persuasively explain why there is a substantial departure,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said Friday in an interview. `` When the appeals courts find the explanations unpersuasive, they've reversed sentences.'' The length of a recommended sentence under the guidelines in the North case would depend partly on a judge deciding whether the former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide substantially interfered with the administration of justice. Other factors would be the value assigned to classified documents that <PERSON> North </PERSON> destroyed, whether he was a major or minor participant in the crime of aiding the obstruction of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and whether he was considered to be in a high-level decision-making capacity.
</TEXT>
