<HEAD>Justice Department Joins Shoreham Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, saying <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> nuclear power plant is `` safe, efficient and much-needed,'' is joining in a lawsuit to prevent the plant from being dismantled The intervention in a state court came on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which has strongly opposed the shutdown of the 813-megawatt plant on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Henson </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, deputy energy secretary, said the state, in its approval of the dismantling plan, had not adequately considered the impact on the environment. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> argues that the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> and the state <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> should have prepared formal environmental impact statements before approving the plan. The plant, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said, is `` safe, efficient and much-needed,'' adding that its closure would require the region to rely more heavily on fossil fuel. Those fuels, he said, will have `` adverse environmental consequences'' through the increased release of chemicals that contribute to acid rain and global warming. Some <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> residents and a group called Scientists and <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Secure </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> filed the suit against the plant. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration previously has made clear its opposition to the closing of the $ 5.5 billion plant completed in 1985 and licensed last year. It has yet to produce any commercial electricity. State and local officials contend the plant should not be allowed to operate because evacuation of the area 50 miles east of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> would be impossible. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> plans to meet with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> next week to discuss White House opposition to the plant being torn down.
