<HEAD>Two Protesters, Man Who Torched Clinic Guilty in Abortion Racketeering
Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `He and ...' to clarify that all three were found
to have conspired to violate the racketeering statute; picks up 5th graf,
`Beseda was ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two abortion protesters and a man who insisted <PERSON> God </PERSON> told him to set fire to an abortion clinic conspired to violate federal racketeering laws, a federal court jury ruled Friday in a civil lawsuit. <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Beseda </PERSON>, already serving 20 years in a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> federal prison for setting fire to the Feminist Women's <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Everett </LOCATION>, also violated the racketeering statute through arson and extortion aimed at the abortion clinic, the jury concluded. The Everett clinic was burned three times between December 1983 and April 1984, then closed its doors. <PERSON> Beseda </PERSON> earlier told the jury he had no intention of setting any fire until he heard God tell him to do it. He and protesters <PERSON> Dottie </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Codispoti </PERSON>, both of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stevens </LOCATION>, were found to have conspired to violate the racketeering statute. <PERSON> Beseda </PERSON> was ordered to pay $ 268,500 in civil damages while <PERSON> Beseda </PERSON>, <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> and <PERSON> Codispoti </PERSON> will share another $ 11,000 fine. All damages can be trebled. Two other defendants, <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Undseth </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Snohomish </LOCATION>, were acquitted. Jurors in Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Zilly </PERSON>'s court deliberated 3 -LCB- days before reaching a verdict in the month-long trial. The lawsuit is only the second time the racketeering statute, intended to fight organized crime, has been used against abortion protesters. Damages will go to several clinic employees and to the <ORGANIZATION> Feminist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yakima </ORGANIZATION>, parent clinic to the one that burned. <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>' lawyer <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Schrempp </PERSON> promised an appeal. <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, holding her young grandson <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON>, said she thinks the jury was confused by the complexity of the case, involving 52 pages of jury instructions. `` It's a perversion of the First Amendment,'' she said. `` This one's going to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.'' She said the plaintiffs `` wo n't get anything out of me ... because I do n't have anything. In <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, the case that set precedent in the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> case was upheld on appeal in March and defendants have asked the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to hear it. Twenty-six individuals were found guilty of multiple acts of extortion at an abortion clinic there. The clinic was awarded $ 100,000. Lawyers for the plaintiffs alleged <PERSON> Beseda </PERSON> and the other defendants conspired to shut down the clinic by arson, personal and telephone harassment of patients and staff, blocking access to and from the clinic, picketing and helping <PERSON> Beseda </PERSON> escape to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. A successful action under the racketeering statute must show an enterprise adversely affects interstate commerce and engages in a pattern of racketeering, meaning a serious violation of the law such as arson, extortion, wire fraud, robbery, kidnapping or murder, said <PERSON> Edmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiryak </PERSON>, the civil rights attorney who tried the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> case.
