<HEAD>Peugeot Shows Worst Injury Potential In Government Crash Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crash tests indicate that a driver of a <ORGANIZATION> Peugeot </ORGANIZATION> 505S has a greater chance of head injury than drivers of 28 other cars and small trucks tested so far, federal engineers say. However, a <ORGANIZATION> Peugeot </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the tests conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> using instrument-equipped dummies do n't accurately test the effects of real highway accidents. `` Our top concern is protecting human beings, not dummies,'' <PERSON> Pascal </PERSON> <PERSON> Henault </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Peugeot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, said Friday. The new series of tests included 10 different car and van models by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and foreign automaker. In previous tests involving 19 vehicles, the Chevrolet Astro Van fared worst. The Astro now stands second among cars tested for injuries in a 35-mile-per-hour collision. The vehicles were tested under <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION>'s program to provide consumers a guide to the safety of 1989 cars and small trucks. The car in which the lightest injury potential was recorded so far is the <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daytona </ORGANIZATION>, followed by the Ford Thunderbird and the <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 80. The <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> was among the 10 cars tested in the most recent round. Others, in addition to the Peugeot 505S, were <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sonata </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Isuzu </ORGANIZATION> Trooper II, <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Sidekick </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Toyota </PERSON> <PERSON> Cressida </PERSON>, Corolla, pickup and van. After the latest tests were made public, <ORGANIZATION> Peugeot </ORGANIZATION> issued a news release including comments from <PERSON> Henault </PERSON> and from four automotive and consumer experts who criticized the government tests as inaccurate measures of the varied circumstances that exist in real crashes. `` <ORGANIZATION> Peugeot </ORGANIZATION>'s commitment to building cars that are safe in the real world can not be overshadowed by these experimental crash-test results,'' said <PERSON> Henault </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> tests consist of crashing a single model of each car containing two crash dummies into a fixed barrier at 35 mph. The stresses that result on the dummies are measured by sensors. The artificial occupants are protected by seat belts and other safety devices used in the cars. <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> engineers reported stresses on the head as an index called the `` head injury criterion.'' The higher the index, the greater the likelihood of injury. The Peugeot crash produced a head injury criterion of 1,983 on the driver-side dummy. The earlier Astro test registered 1,849. Federal regulations require cars to produce a head injury criterion no greater than 1,000 in tests conducted by the automakers at 30 mph. The <ORGANIZATION> NHTSA </ORGANIZATION> tests are not considered comparable because they are done at a speed 5 mph faster. The tests are continuing, but here is how all models so far tested rank in head injury criterion to the driver: <ORGANIZATION> Peugeot </ORGANIZATION> 505S, 1,983; <PERSON> Chevrolet </PERSON> <PERSON> Astro </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON>, 1,849; <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> Pickup, 1,520; <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spirit </ORGANIZATION>, 1,421; <ORGANIZATION> Suzuki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sidekick </ORGANIZATION>, 1,345; <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caprice </ORGANIZATION>, 1,328; <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> Trooper II, 1,269; <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Van </ORGANIZATION>, 1,183; <ORGANIZATION> Hyundai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sonata </ORGANIZATION>, 1,196; <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corolla </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bronco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION>, 994; <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Galant </ORGANIZATION>, 971; <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Probe, 970; Jeep Cherokee, 968; <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirage </ORGANIZATION>, 960. Others were the Mercury Tracer, 940; <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Premier </ORGANIZATION>, 877; <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, 863; Chevrolet S10 Blazer, 834; <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Van </ORGANIZATION>, 805; <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cressida </ORGANIZATION>, 790; <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION>, 787; <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> 5th Avenue, 786; <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> CRX </ORGANIZATION>, 750; Eagle Medallion, 745; <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acclaim </ORGANIZATION>, 663; <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 80, 600; Ford Thunderbird, 541; <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daytona </ORGANIZATION>, 399.
