<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Panamanian troops briefly detained American soldiers in another confrontation between both sides, and Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> again indicated he has no intention of stepping down as <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s leader. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> today marked six years as head of the Panamanian <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> and the nation's de facto ruler. He said Friday that a plebiscite proposed by the opposition for Aug. 20 on whether he should resign was tantamount to turning <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> into `` a colony that accepts arrogance, vassalage and indignity.'' He spoke during a parade of thousands of troops and paramilitary civilian units ending a 10-day exercise called `` Zap the Intruder.'' White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Friday that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration `` would not rule out'' seizing <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and taking him to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to face drug trafficking charges. But <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was not contemplating such a move at this time. The latest confrontation between Panamanian and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops occurred in a remote area known as <LOCATION> Curundu </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> says the area is a military zone shared by both countries, while the Panamanians claim it is exclusively their domain. A Defense Forces patrol detained four vehicles carrying a number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military police, and the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> said it quickly dispatched troops backed by armored cars and helicopters. The incident started when `` American t