<HEAD>Bloch Says He Was In Paris In May, Leaves Open Spying Question</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Suspended <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> said he was in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> the day he allegedly left a briefcase in a restaurant for a Soviet agent, but he declined to confirm or deny spying allegations against him. <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> spoke in an Austrian television and radio interview broadcast Friday from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. It was the second time in the past week that he declined opportunities in interviews with Austrian media to deny the suspicions. The Austrian-born diplomat, formerly the No. 2 man in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, was suspended from the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on June 22 In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> Friday said public disclosure of its investigation of <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, 54, had compromised the government's ability to obtain evidence against him. `` There is no doubt that the premature disclosure of that case, the premature disclosure that there was an ongoing investigation, did compromise the investigation,'' department spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Runkel </PERSON> said without elaboration. No charges have been brought against <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>. He remains under investigation and surveillance by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, and reporters have followed him around <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in recent days. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> has reported that on May 14, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and met his alleged contact for dinner. <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> left his briefcase under the table to be picked up by the suspected Soviet agent, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> said. Asked by Austrian TV correspondent <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiesner </PERSON> whether he was in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> May 14, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> said after a long pause, `` Yes.'' He declined, however, to specify whether he met <PERSON> Reino </PERSON> <PERSON> Gikman </PERSON>, a man holding Finnish documents who regularly visited <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> during <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>'s 1980-87 tour in the Austrian capital. <PERSON> Gikman </PERSON> has been identified by Austrian and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities as a suspected <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agent who might have been a contact man. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sources have said <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> contends he only knew the man as a stamp collector. When <PERSON> Wiesner </PERSON> pressed <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> for details of the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> trip, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> said, `` I was in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> May 14. I was in a restaurant, and there were very many people in that restaurant, and I enjoyed the food there very much.'' `` Have you missed your briefcase since?'' asked <PERSON> Wiesner </PERSON>. After another long pause, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON>, who seemed relaxed and spoke in his native German, said: `` No.'' <PERSON> Wiesner </PERSON> repeatedly pressed <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> to deny he was a spy. `` Why do n't you just say it was all just invented?'' he asked. `` I could say much on this topic, but I will restrain myself,'' <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> answered. By remaining silent, <PERSON> Wiesner </PERSON> noted, <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> only heightens suspense. `` I do n't want people to feel bored during August,'' <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> said, smiling. `` Are the accusations against you justified?'' <PERSON> Wiesner </PERSON> asked again several minutes later. `` This question I can not answer now,'' <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> responded. In a much briefer interview in the current issu