<HEAD>`Sweetheart City' Becomes Haven for Sculptors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOVELAND, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two foundries and a willingness to support public art has turned the `` Sweetheart City,'' long known as the town with the special Valentine's Day postmark, into a haven for sculptors. `` Art is in focus all the time here,'' said sculptor <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, 59, who moved to <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> in 1978 from <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. `` We've infiltrated the <ORGANIZATION> Rotary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, all kinds of groups. About 40 professional sculptors have moved to the northern <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> city, most of them in the past five years, and dozens of others come to town part of the year to work with <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION>'s two foundries. <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> is smitten with sculpture, displaying its own collection along roadsides, at a sculpture park, around a new Civic Center, and in galleries and studios around town. This weekend, the city is the site of one of the largest sculpture shows in the world, Sculpture in the Park. Nearly 190 sculptors from around the nation are exhibiting work, and officials hope the show will net the city even more than the $ 3.5 million it did last year. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hallsten </PERSON> <PERSON> McGarry </PERSON>, editor of Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>, called both the town and the huge sculpture show, `` a pretty major force ... as to an actual art event that changes every year with different people bringing new work, I do n't think you can get a broader exposure to a larger number of working sculptors anywhere in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The city about 40 miles north of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> that has struggled to become known for something more than a place to get a special Valentine's Day postal cancellation began its love affair with sculpture back in 1972. Then, a local metal foundry that made parts for <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> began casting bronze for sculptures and soon was accepting work from artists around the region. Eventually, it drew the artists themselves to <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION>, giving many of them jobs in the business. A second foundry, <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> Sculpture Works, was started by former employees of the original foundry, Art Castings of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. Five sculptors who had come to <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> to be near the foundry _ <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundeen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ostermiller </PERSON>, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Walbye </PERSON>, White and <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> <PERSON> Williford </PERSON> _ approached the city several years ago about helping promote the arts. The result was the private <ORGANIZATION> Loveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plains </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which raises money to buy works and then donates them to the city. The city does its part as well. In 1985, <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> became the first <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> city to pass an ordinance setting aside 1 percent of the construction costs of any public project over $ 50,000 to buy original artwork. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ison </PERSON>, director of the city's <ORGANIZATION> Visual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> now has more than $ 1 million worth of art. In return, the influx of artists breathes new life into the city's economy and cultural life. `` It's an industry in itself,'' City Manager <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Rock </PERSON> said of sculpture, which employs more than 400 people in the community of 38,200. <PERSON> Rock </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION>'s commitment to the arts has helped economic development efforts. `` We can demonstrate to a company that it's a fairly sophisticated community _ it has hometown values but an unmatched level of art, and many community-minded citizens,'' he said. Downtown merchants, too, are sponsoring a sculpture park on a prime corner to help attract more people. For the artists, that kind of attention and camaraderie make <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> an attractive place. <PERSON> White </PERSON> <PERSON> Williford </PERSON> moved to <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> nine years ago to be `` in the foundry's hip pocket.'' Above all, <PERSON> Williford </PERSON> said, he likes the cooperative atmosphere among <LOCATION> Loveland </LOCATION> sculptors. `` In a large city, it's more dog-eat-dog. People are less willing to share. There's too many rats in a cage. When artists back East come visit and we open our doors to them, they ca n't believe it.
