<HEAD>Passengers On Derailed Train Were Headed For Work U.S. Or Visiting
Relatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUASAVE, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> coast whistle-stop train that derailed and killed 112 people carried many would-be illegal aliens who had planned to slip into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to find work. A bridge weakened by floods and torrential rain collapsed Wednesday, pitching the train into the swirling <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rafael </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> 15 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Guasave </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Survivor <PERSON> Cirilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> said Friday he had hoped to cross the boarder into <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to escape subsistence farming in <LOCATION> Etla </LOCATION> <LOCATION> la </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Villa </LOCATION> in the southern state of <LOCATION> Oaxaca </LOCATION>. He traveled to the <LOCATION> Sonora </LOCATION> state beach resort of <LOCATION> Mazatlan </LOCATION>, and from there took the train for the 700-mile ride to <LOCATION> Mexicali </LOCATION>, across the border from <LOCATION> Calexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. It would have been his first attempt to find work in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` From growing corn and beans and burning oak to sell as charcoal, I do n't make anything, just enough to eat,'' said <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>, 40, a Mexican of Indian descent who spoke Spanish with difficulty. <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> said his youngest son, 16 years old, has finished junior high school but may not be able to study further. `` I do n't have the money for him to go to school. That's why I was going to look for a way to earn a living,'' <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> said in an interview at the <LOCATION> Social </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Security </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inistitute </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, where he was recovering from injuries. He said he hoped to be released today and then would decide whether to continue his trip to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Sinaloa </LOCATION> state health coordinator <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Campana </PERSON> said of the more than 200 injured in the train derailment, 10 remained hospitalized. About 400 people and four helicopters have been searching for more victims, state security coordinator <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Saracho </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Saracho </PERSON> said no more bodies were found Friday, but that the search was to resume early today. Another would-be illegal alien, <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, said the $ 5 a day he earned working at a taco stand in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> was not enough to feed his wife and four children and keep the eldest, a 9-year-old, in school. `` I was going to cross the border. That was my intention,'' he said. But the train crash left him with a leg fracture that will require surgery, and doctors told him he would not be able to work for at least three months. Many people on the train also were en route to visit relatives or just completing summer vacations. People who still had not heard from relatives on the train continued to arrive in <LOCATION> Guasava </LOCATION> on Friday, making the rounds of government offices and hospitals. Officials buried 38 unidentified bodies in the Guasave cemetary, their plots marked by white, nameless crosses. With the burials, relatives had to try to identify the missing from photographs of the bodies.
