<FIRST>r a PM-Railroad-Indians     08-12 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Railroad-Indians,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Southern Pacific Agrees to Pay $1.2 Million in Indian Land Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A railroad company will pay an Indian tribe $ 1.2 million to end a century-old dispute over reservation land acquired in the 1860s when the industry steamed its way West. `` As far as the railroad is concerned, we've settled with the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> and we're out of it,'' <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said Friday. `` How the money is distributed is up to the government and the tribe. Representatives for the <LOCATION> Walker </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paiute </LOCATION> tribe could not be reached by telephone for comment on the trespassing case. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> McKibben </PERSON> on Wednesday signed an order approving the $ 1.2 million settlement, which will be held by the court until officials decide how to distribute the money. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said the class-action lawsuit potentially involves from 300 to 500 <LOCATION> Walker </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> Paiutes who could get a share of the settlement. The tribe initially sought as much as $ 16 million, while the railroad said the disputed land was worth only about $ 750 when <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> acquired it. The railroad at first offered a $ 30,000 settlement in the case. The dispute involves about 400 acres in west-central <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Wabuska </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> to near the northern end of the <LOCATION> Walker </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Mineral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. The tribe filed suit in 1972 because the railroad never officially gained congressional approval for a right of way through the <LOCATION> Walker </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reservation </LOCATION> to lay out its tracks. The <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> said that as a result, <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> was trespassing and the tribe should be compensated for the use of the land that rightfully should belong to the Paiutes. The <ORGANIZATION> 9th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> agreed with the Indians that the railroad failed to comply with several federal acts governing tribal lands. The appeals court last year remanded the case to the district level to award trespassing damages to the tribe. More than 100 year ago, the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> agreed to take $ 750 for the land along with the promise from <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> for free rides to Indians forever. The railroad agreed, but never built passenger cars for the trains that ran on the line, which carried mostly explosives for area military operations and other goods. As a result, Indians were forced to ride in boxcars or cattle cars or on top of the trains, sometimes falling off, according to old newspaper clippings. `` Members of the tribe were basically treated like cattle,'' says <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, economist who studied the history of the line for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
