<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A custodian has been declared the winner of a $ 3 million Lotto jackpot even though he has no winning ticket to show for it. Sixty-year-old <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> claimed he lost the ticket. Circuit Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sklodowski </PERSON> believed him, and ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lottery </ORGANIZATION> to make him a millionaire. `` <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> provided evidence that he consistantly played the same two sets of numbers on a weekly basis, and the lottery verified that the winning ticket was purchased at the store where <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> said he always bought his tickets,'' said <PERSON> Sklodowski </PERSON> in making the ruling Thursday. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lahr </PERSON>, an attorney for the lottery, said the 60-year-old <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> did show officials other tickets with the winning numbers, but all are dated after the Nov. 9, 1985, drawing, <PERSON> Lahr </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, lottery director, said the state has n't decided whether to appeal the ruling. The lottery no longer has the $ 3 million, which has been turned over to the state. If the ruling stands, the lottery may have to ask for a special appropriation, Ms. <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> played the same numbers each week _ 4-14-16-29-37-41 _ said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Andjelkovich </PERSON>, <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>'s attorney. <PERSON> Andjelkovich </PERSON> said <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> did n't find out he had won until a year after the drawing, when <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Julie </PERSON>, recognized the winning number in a newspaper article that said no one had yet claimed the $ 3 million Lotto prize. `` <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> screamed ` Oh my God!' and started digging through his lottery tickets,'' <PERSON> Andjelkovich </PERSON> said. `` But he could n't find it.'' <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> and 22 other people filed claims with the lottery for the prize. All were rejected because none had the actual ticket, Ms. <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON> said.
