<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strike     08-12 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strike,0544</SECOND>
<UNK>Justice Minister Warns Estonian Voting Law Illegal</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet justice minister said <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>'s effort to tighten voting residency laws that have sparked a strike by thousands of <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> workers is unconstitutional. A nationwide newspaper placed the number of strikers in the small Baltic republic at about 40,000, more than twice as many as local journalists and the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency estimated. <PERSON> Veniamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON>, Soviet justice minister, Friday told the evening television news program `` Vremya'' that <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> ought to reconsider the law, which sets residence requirements to protect Estonians' hold on the republic. `` I think it's obvious that this Estonian law does n't correspond to our constitution,'' <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> said. `` This means that a significant portion of the population will be left out.'' <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> said the law, passed Tuesday, also violated international conventions on civil rights that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has signed. But instead of flatly declaring the law void, <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> appealed to the Estonian Supreme Soviet to reconsider it. Under the law, residents of <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> can not vote unless they have lived in the same district for at least two years, or have lived anywhere in the republic for a total of five years. Candidates for elective office must live in the same place for five years, or in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> for 10 years. Russian-speaking workers walked off their jobs the day after the law was passed, and sent a delegation to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to seek meetings with national officials. <PERSON> Vasily </PERSON> <PERSON> Makismov </PERSON>, a member of the strike committee, said in an interview from <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION> that one member of the delegation had returned and was meeting with strikers this morning. <PERSON> Maksimov </PERSON> said railroad stations were on strike and that the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> airline was shipping only emergency items such as medical supplies and equipment. Passenger service was not affected. The newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Sotsialisticheskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industriya </ORGANIZATION> reported today that more than 30 factories and other state-run businesses were on strike, including about 40,000 workers. `` Dialogue between the leaders of the republic and the strikers has practically come to a halt,'' it said. The Estonian leadership acknowledged in a statement released Friday that it failed to `` take into account fully the growth of national consciousness among the non-Estonian population of the republic,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. The Estonian parliament banned strikes Thursday, but the strikers ignored the action. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> on Friday put the number of strikers in <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION> at 16,000. A few enterprises in <LOCATION> Kokhla-Jarve </LOCATION>, a mining town east of <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION>, also were reported to be on strike. Strike committee members said workers at 42 Estonian factories and firms walked out, but local journalists said they counted only about 24 Estonian enterprises with striking employees. Non-Estonian residents of the republic, including leaders of the Russian-dominated InterMovement group, complain the law is aimed at them because many are new arrivals. They are also upset by a law making Estonian the official language. Ethnic Estonians make up slightly more than 60 percent of the population. Russians make up about a third of the 1.6 million people. <PERSON> Sotsialisticheskaya </PERSON> <PERSON> Industriya </PERSON> quoted striking workers as complaining that they want to get into courses to learn Estonian, but that the few available are crowded and expensive.
