<HEAD>Search Intensified With Four Helicopters, Distress Signal Site Rechecked</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with four U.S. helicopters joining search, one
distress signal area rechecked, rough weather, ADDS background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blackhawk </ORGANIZATION> helicopters joined an aerial search today for Rep. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> and 15 others missing since their plane left for a southwestern refugee camp five days ago. Also today, Ethiopian helicopters rechecked one of two areas outside the plane's flight path where a satellite picked up an apparent distress signal, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Haley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in the capital. The UH-60 Blackhawk helicopters arrived Friday from <ORGANIZATION> Eglin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and joined two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> C-130 Hercules cargo planes in the search of the rugged mountains southwest of the capital, <PERSON> Haley </PERSON> said. `` They are capable of staying in the air all day because the C-130s have refueling capability,'' <PERSON> Haley </PERSON> said. He said search efforts by the C-130s was concentrated on the intended flight path of the twin-engine plane that disappeared Monday with <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> on board. The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Hunger, was accompanied by eight other Americans. The Twin Otter aircraft, owned by <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s government relief agency, was en route from <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION> to the Fugnido refugee camp 450 miles away near the Sudanese border. The C-130s joined the search Thursday when they arrived from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Haley </PERSON> said today that the weather `` was not cooperating, but they are able to search.'' Weather has hampered the search since it began Tuesday and may have played a role in the disappearance of the Canadian-made plane, which seats up to 20 passengers. Officials have said the plane's takeoff Monday morning was delayed two hours by rough weather and that it departed in heavy clouds and poor visibility The site of the apparent distress signal being checked again is in an area around <LOCATION> Goba </LOCATION> about 85 miles southeast of the capital, <PERSON> Haley </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has said its weather satellites picked up signals in that area as well as about 100 miles north of <LOCATION> Addis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ababa </LOCATION>. A land and air search of both areas on Friday turned up nothing. Asked how the satellites could have recorded false signals, <PERSON> Haley </PERSON> replied, `` I've been trying to get an answer to that myself.'' <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>'s plane was equipped with an emergency locator transmittor, a device usually mouted in the tail of an aircraft and activated either automatically by impact or manually by the pilot. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Friday the passengers had some box lunches, one or two cases of soft drinks and 35 gallons of water. The prospect of temperatures that can drop to freezing at night was a troubling factor. Planes must fly over mountainous terrain to reach the Fugnido refugee camp, but the route was not over the area where rebels are battling <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s government. <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s separatist movements are based in the northern part of the country in the Horn of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. A spokeswoman for <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> complained Friday that the rescue effort lacked urgency. `` With all of the sophisticated surveillance that we have, with all of the sophisticated equipment we have, we should have located them by now,'' <PERSON> Alma </PERSON> <PERSON> Newsom </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> defended the search efforts, which involved scores of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel. `` I can understand the anxiety of all this and I can understand the concern that people that love <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> feel and that I feel,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` But there's a lot going on, so let's just hope and pray he's OK.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said late Friday that 170 military personnel had been assigned to the search and that the number soon would reach 260 <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. Gen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Record </PERSON>, director of operations for <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, was to leave today to take charge of the search, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. The Pentagon said in a statement that two U-2 photographic reconnaissance planes had exposed more than a mile of film in runs over the 56,000-square mile search area, of which about 60 percent was covered by clouds. Twelve Ethiopian helicopters also participated in the search. <PERSON> Haley </PERSON> said the eight other Americans aboard included three members of <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>'s staff, a friend of the congressman's, three officers of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGA