<HEAD>Animal Activists Disrupt Start of Grouse Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Animal rights campaigners crept onto moors before dawn in northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> today to disrupt an already quiet Glorious Twelfth of August, the traditional opening of the grouse season. About 90 supporters of the Hunt Saboteurs' Association occupied two northern English moors in <LOCATION> Geltsdale </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Carlisle </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Stanhope </PERSON> to shoo away the birds, said a spokesman, <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponton </PERSON>. `` The action will go on as long as it has to,'' he said. `` The shooting parties are driving around but have made no attempt to get onto the moors.'' Another 100 members had also gathered in <LOCATION> Bowland </LOCATION> but thick mist had kept hunters away, said <PERSON> Ponton </PERSON>, whose group annually tries to disrupt the shooting of the prized game. Aristocrats and wealthy tourists organize hunting parties on Scottish and English moors to kick off the Glorious Twelfth, and in past years restaurants have vied to bring the birds to the table. But this year disease has decimated the flocks, leading to the cancellation of many shoots. `` Grouse numbers are 20 percent down in some parts of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> and there's no shooting at all today in parts of the north of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'' where populations have fallen 50 percent, said Dr. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> of the private research group the Game Conservancy. Influenced by the animal protesters of recent years and worries over declining numbers of the birds, hotels and restaurants have all but dropped their own colorful races to serve the birds. The prestigious Gleneagles Hotel, once a forerunner in the competition, said it will donate the money it would have used for the race to grouse preservation research for a fifth year. But the bird will still feature on the menu of some restaurants, served with thin fried potatoes, parsley and a bread sauce.
