<HEAD>Tamils: More Than 50 Civilians Killed in Indian Army Offensive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Indian troops killed at least 51 civilians after being attacked by Tamil rebels in a northern town, Tamil sources said today. The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 40 houses and 23 shops were set on fire by the soldiers after an army patrol was ambushed Aug. 2 in the town of <LOCATION> Velvettiturai </LOCATION>, 200 miles north of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. At least six soldiers were killed in the attack, military officials said at the time. The Tamil sources, who have proved reliable in the past, quoted residents as saying the Indian peacekeeping troops imposed a 48-hour curfew on Velvettiturai after the ambush and carried out search operations. Many houses were shelled and several people were burned to death, the sources said. They said that 51 victims were identified by relatives after the curfew was withdrawn. The <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, the rebel group fighting the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement telexed to newspaper offices that at least 70 civilians were killed in the offensive. The <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>' accounts of casualties have proved to be exaggerated in the past Sri Lankan military officials confirmed a major operation by Indian troops occurred in <LOCATION> Velvettiturai </LOCATION>, but they said they did not have details because they do not operate in the Tamil-dominated areas of the country. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, a government spokesman said there were 18 civilian casualties in an exchange of gunfire between the soldiers and the rebels after the ambush. He said the rebels used civilians as cover while firing with rocket-propelled grenades and automatic rifles at the Indian army patrol. `` The troops returned fire and 30 bodies were recovered after the fighting,'' said the spokesman, who can not be identified under briefing rules. `` At least five were hard-core <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> and seven others were sympathizers.'' `` Eighteen unfortunate civilians were killed in the cross fire,'' he said. The spokesman denied that civilians were killed during the curfew. `` The Tamils in <LOCATION> Velvettiturai </LOCATION> will say whatever the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> tell them to,'' he said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>' capacity to kill fellow Tamils is unlimited and they live in fear of retribution.'' Indian soldiers have been in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s Tamil-dominated north and east for the past two years to put down the Tamil war for an independent homeand. They were deployed to supervise an India-sponsored accord under which <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> offered Tamils limited autonomy in exchange for an arms surrender. But the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> rejected the agreement and turned their guns on the Indians. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> got involved because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils to the rebel cause. Tamils comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people and allege they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of the population and control the government and the military. Militant Tamils launched their separatist war in 1983. At least 11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have been killed in the fighting.
