<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> gunners locked in one of their fiercest battles in months pummeled the <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> area today in an exchange that reportedly left at least 12 people dead and 48 wounded. Smoke from shells and fires in nearby hills hung like a funeral shroud over the city. Five months of such duels have prompted all but about 200,000 of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s 1.5 million residents to flee. Police said at least 12 people were killed and 48 wounded in today's fighting between Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s 20,000 predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> troops and 40,000 Syrian soldiers and their Moslem militia allies. More than 40 have died in the past two days, bringing the toll since March 8 to 598 killed and 1,562 wounded, according to security sources. Radios interrupted their programs with bulletins about where shells were falling and to report fires blazing out of control in several parts of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. A police spokesman said fierce clashes with machine guns, recoilless cannons and rocket-propelled grenade launchers raged across <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s dividing Green Line and the eastern flank of the Christian enclave. Acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, who heads the Moslem cabinet vying for power with the military cabinet under <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, said: `` We're left in the blowing wind with no roof above us. `` The problem in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> is that our wise people are not active and our active people are not wise,'' <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> said in a statement broadcast by <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION> radio. The French and Argentine embassies in neighboring <LOCATION> Baabda </LOCATION> were hit by Syrian rockets and one French embassy guard was slightly wounded,