e, shattering a two-hour lull in the fighting. The whooshing sound of outgoing rockets echoed across the mountains southeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. A few minutes later, howitzer shells fired by <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s gunners crashed into the region, sending palls of dust and smoke into the sky. Syrian soldiers deserted their sand-bagged checkpoints at the <LOCATION> Khaldeh </LOCATION> junction south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and sought refuge in fox holes along the sandy coast. Several motorists abandoned their cars and fled under the main highway bridge in <LOCATION> Khaldeh </LOCATION>. Others sped away. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s gunners, using 155-mm U.S.-made howitzers, concentrated their shelling on Syrian artillery emplacements, truck-mounted rocket launchers and communications posts in the hills of <LOCATION> Aramoun </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Doha </LOCATION>, above <LOCATION> Khaldeh </LOCATION>. A howitzer shell, fired by <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s gunners, scored a direct hit on a 40-barrel rocket launcher on a hilltop in <LOCATION> Aramoun </LOCATION>, setting it on fire. Black smoke billowed from the truck-mounted launcher for 20 minutes, during which the Syrians intensified their shelling of the Christian enclave, operating more than a dozen rocket launchers in unison. Security sources said rockets and shells fired by Syrian gunners targeted almost every town and village in the 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of the capital.
