 <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> `` Radar'' <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, a short hitter playing on a long course, took a two-stroke lead today into the third round of the 71st PGA championship. <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> shot 34-33_67 in Friday's rain-delayed round to go with his opening round of 66 for an 11-under-par 133. Trailing <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> were <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, who shared the first-round lead with <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Stadler </PERSON> at 135. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, another stroke back at 136, was seeking the only major championship he has not won in his quest for a rare career grand slam of the major tournaments. <PERSON> Stadler </PERSON> shot a course record 33-31_64 in a bogey-free second round for his 135. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicklaus </PERSON> and <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> made the cut of one-over-par 145 for the top 70 scorers. <PERSON> Nicklaus </PERSON> had a four-under 140 and <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, who electrified the crowds Thursday with a 68, had a second-round 74 for 142. Grouped at 137 were <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Rummells </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiori </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bean </PERSON>. U. S. Open champion <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Strange </PERSON> was at 138. Defending champion <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Sluman </PERSON> and pre-tournament favorite <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> barely made the cut at 145. Failing to make the cut were former PGA champions <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Trevino </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lanny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wadkins </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahaffey </PERSON>, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Tway </PERSON>. Ot