<HEAD>Reason For Shuttle Landing Secrecy? Well, It's Sort Of Secret</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Officials declined...', to add time of landing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The desert site where up to 500,000 people have cheered past space shuttle landings will be empty when <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> returns to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, closed by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> for unexplained security reasons. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> said the secrecy was necessary to `` to limit an adversary's ability to determine the mission of a given <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION> shuttle flight.'' <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> said Wednesday that <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s crew deployed an important satellite He declined to elaborate, but sources close to the project have said the 10-ton satellite is designed to snap highly-detailed photographs of military targets over a large area of the globe, including most of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Officials declined to elaborate on how national security might be harmed by opening the public viewing site for <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s landing, scheduled for 9:37 EDT Sunday `` I really do n't know,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Haley </PERSON>, a civilian spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> at this <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> military base. The site is located 3 -LCB- miles from where the shuttle rolls to a stop on dry lakebed runway 17. It drew 500,000 spectators when <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> was greeted by then-President and Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on July 4, 1982. It has been closed during classified military shuttle missions. While the public is barred, reporters, photographers and television camera operators will be allowed to watch and record <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s landing from a media site about 2 miles from the shuttle's stopping point. `` It's crazy. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> likes to play I've It makes them feel more important,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pike </PERSON>, space policy analyst for the <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scientists </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Pike </PERSON> said during a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that he understands <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s payload was a modified version of the KH-12 photoreconnaissance satellite. Secrecy surrounding the shuttle `` is not protecting this mission from the Russians. It's protecting this mission from the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> taxpayers,'' he said. Capt. <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> <PERSON> Hauser </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, disagreed. <PERSON> Hauser </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials `` feel we do a good job of keeping the public informed through the media and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. ... We have a very effective way of reporting on the programs we have to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> select intelligence committees.''
