<HEAD>Hopes Raised In Central America With Summit Accord</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The agreement by Central American presidents to disband U.S.-supported Nicaraguan rebels has raised hopes and added momentum to the quest for peace in the region after a decade of conflict. `` We Central American presidents have taken the destiny of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in our own hands,'' said Costa Rican President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> after the accords were signed Aug. 7 in the Honduran port of <PERSON> Tela </PERSON>. The presidents of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> have committed themselves to disband the 11,000 Contra rebels camped in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> near the Nicaraguan border by early December. The deal was sealed after the others apparently concluded <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> was genuinely moving towards a fair election, as he had promised so many times in the past. Although Central American deadlines have not often been honored, the end of the eight-year-old Nicaraguan war seems to be in sight. The presidents widened the spotlight to include <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. The outlook remains problematic, but the call for a cease-fire and democratic guarantees has provided the best opportunity in years for progress towards ending a conflict that began in 1980. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration said the Contras should not be disbanded until after <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s presidential vote, set for Feb. 25, 1990, in order to keep the heat on the leftist Sandinista government. But after eight years of fighting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position appeared sterile. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been unwilling to approve military aid that would restore the Contras as an effective force. <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> receive hundreds of millions of dollars in aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but sources at the talks said the Central Americans concluded relations would not be hurt by a decision to disband the Contras _ something that appeared inevitable in any case. Besides, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> was seen as moving towards an accommodation with its domestic opposition. Just before the summit, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> obtained an agreement in which the opposition joined a call for the Contras' demise in return for promises of electoral reform. The move made <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s promises of democratization more credible, and <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> sweetened the deal for <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>' <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> by agreeing to drop a world court suit against <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> for abetting subversion of another government. <PERSON> Emilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Montalvan </PERSON>, a conservative Nicaraguan politician, attributed the eased tensions to the superpower thaw and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of `` perestroika,'' or economic and political restructuring. Like the Contras, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> has had to deal with reduced support from his allies; on Thursday, a Soviet official told <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will ship halt arms shipments to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> as a contributioon to the peace process `` Neither side is interested in using Third World conflicts to get at the other any more,'' <PERSON> Montalvan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ungo </PERSON>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s most prominent leftist politician, noted that three presidents _ <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON>, <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vinicio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cerezo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> _ are near the ends of their terms. `` They wanted to go down on the record as having achieved something concretely positive for regional peace,'' said <PERSON> Ungo </PERSON>, who finished a poor third to President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s voting earlier this year. <PERSON> Ungo </PERSON> predicted <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> `` will continue trying to block implementation of the Tela accords.'' But President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will face a fight in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> if he tries to extend even non-lethal aid to the Contras in the face of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> political agreements. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>' popularity has been hurt by an economy that is on its way to becoming the hemisphere's worst. The government blames it on the war and a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embargo. The opposition blames it on rigid economic policies. Even so, the <PERSON> Sandinistas </PERSON> are still favored in 1990, and <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> has improved his odds by suspending the draft. With the Contras fading, the political benefits outweighed the military need, although occasional fighting continues in the countryside. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> also have agreed to free certain political prisoners, reopen a television channel for the opposition, allow <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> election observers and yield power immediately if the opposition wins. Once the rebels are disbanded, the Tela accord calls for a wide-ranging, unconditional amnesty. The Contra leadership has been reported divided over whether to return to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>; some fear the fighters themselves, largely poor agricultural workers, will not want to lay down their arms. While the opposition is looking for more concessions, the business of politics has begun to pick up steam in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> estimates 1.8 million Nicaraguans will register. The opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> expressed concern about fraud, but added `` the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have absolutely renounced their ` historic project,' which involved holding on to power in order to install a dictatorship.'' The Tela accords, in addition to demobilization of the Contras, call for an end to the Salvadoran war and incorporation of the rebels into the democratic process. Both the government and the rebels hailed the accords and see improved chances for discussing peace, although there was no requirement and no verification or enforcement provision, as there is at the Nicaraguan end. The consensus among Salvadoran politicians is that resolution of the `` Contra question'' in and of itself benefits <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> by giving it attention previously monopolized by <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> agreed not to aid the rebels, but Salvadorans remain skeptical about that. Although the two sides are far apart, the war has been going on for even longer than <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s, without a decisive outcome. Mere fatigue may be enough to push the sides into taking advantage of the <LOCATION> Tela </LOCATION> opening.
