<HEAD>Blacks Returning to Traditional Churches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>EDS: SamsonCampbell is correct ^By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For 10 years, <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> and his wife were the only blacks in their Presbyterian church in <LOCATION> Bucks </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. Now <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> drives 15 miles every Sunday to a small, all-black church he attended years ago `` When you're black, your life experience makes you want a little different format,'' he says. So did the Rev. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a black priest who has been suspended by the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> for forming the <ORGANIZATION> Imani </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, a breakaway black congregation in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Unlike <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON> and his followers, <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> and other blacks interviewed at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>'s annual conference are not breaking away from their mostly Protestant churches. But their sympathies are with <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON>, who was suspended by the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> archdiocese after he said Mass in defiance of Cardinal <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON> on July 2. <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON> says the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> has failed its nearly 2 million black parishioners. He has accused the church of racism. `` We are excited to see him have such a following, because I want to see people go back to church,'' <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON> said in an interview. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters, `` I believe it would be in the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s interest to understand what <PERSON> Father </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON> is saying. `` If they see the African American community as important for inclusion in the church, then they have to have an appeal to that community,'' <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> said in a news conference Wednesday as the four-day meeting ended. `` They have to understand that they are in competition with traditional black churches.'' Blacks and church officials agreed that mainline <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> churches have avoided the Imani Temple type of schism by allowing flexibility to local congregations. `` I think most Protestant churches are far ahead of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in terms of ritual,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> and pastor of the <ORGANIZATION> Cascade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. `` Local churches are free to use the guidelines just as guidelines,'' <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON> said. For years, he said, he has used the hymn, `` Lift Every Voice and Sing,'' a black favorite, as the doxology in place of the traditional `` Praise God from Whom all Blessings Flow.'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Benton </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and a Lutheran, said concerns of blacks and minorities were a major issue in the merger of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to form the <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, effective last year. <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, director of education for the <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> and wife of a Lutheran minister, said the Lutheran church, with its German and Scandinavian underpinnings, `` has been ethnic ever since it was formed.'' But, she said, it is paying more attention to minorities `` at least in words and in policy; if this can be implemented, that will be fine.'' The issue, known in the church as inclusiveness and diversity, is expected to be debated again when the church's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> meets in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Aug. 23-30 <PERSON> Mim </PERSON> <PERSON> Woolbert </PERSON>, a spokeswoman at the church's headquarters in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said, `` As far as worship concerns, I think that is getting to be answered in each local congregation in a different way, depending on the situation.'' At the national office of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Marj </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON>, director of news services, said, `` We can look back at pictures of our general assemblies even 30 years ago, and it will be all white males sitting there.'' Now the moderator, or titular head, of the church, is a black woman, the Rev. <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> SamsonCampbell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. Still, Ms. <PERSON> Carpenter </PERSON> said, blacks `` monitor us very closely ... they call our hands quickly if we are not paying attention to their concerns.'' <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON>, a delegate from the <ORGANIZATION> Louisville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> who described herself as a lifelong Baptist, said, `` I do n't think there is a trend to set up separate churches and that sort of thing because I do n't think that would solve anything. `` I think it's just a matter of people coming together and talking through their differences. At the same time, she said, she could understand the frustration that led <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON> to form the breakaway church. <PERSON> Ridley </PERSON>, minority affairs coordinator for <ORGANIZATION> Bucks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Newtown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said he was not unhappy at the nearly all-white church that he and his wife attended, where he had held a number of church offices, but felt he could be more useful by rejoining the all-black congregation. He said the pastor of the larger church supported his decision to resign and be `` our missionary'' to the smaller congregation. In his new church, he said, he is rediscovering the emotional climate of black worship. `` I have contact again with the old black matriarchs,'' he said. `` They are beautiful. They are something you miss. And the kids. They do their bit in the service. Tears come into your eyes when you see them in their blue pants and blue skirts and white shirts. They read the scripture, they do everything. I had gotten away from all that. `` In a black church, you have to be very, very basic,'' he said. `` Black folks have to feel it, and if you do n't make it so you can feel it, you get bored, so you say, ` Why go?'''
