<HEAD>Prices Rising for Bread, Staples in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the dusty, fly-ridden food bazaars of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, astute merchants check to see if roads are open or if Moslem rebels have closed them before setting the price of rice, flour and other staples. During the past month, the <LOCATION> Logar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION>, the main route to transport grain and produce from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, has been closed. The other key road to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which runs southeast through the city of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, has been closed intermittently, though the government has gotten convoys through guerrilla lines under military escort. For most of the 2.25 million Afghans living in this mile-high capital and facing almost daily rocket attacks by the rebels, the result of the road closures has been a sharp increase in prices on the open market, especially for flour used to make the traditional Afghan flat bread called `` nan.'' `` People are not happy,'' said <PERSON> Gul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON>, a bearded trader selling 7-pound sacks of flour at a market in western <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. `` They are very hungry now because food is too expensive.'' The U.S.-backed guerrillas, who are based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, say soaring prices are exactly what they want. <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sera </PERSON> of the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Hezb-e-islami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalist </ORGANIZATION> group said the guerrilla strategy is to put pressure on the capital and force residents to evacuate, thus paving the way for attacks on the city and the ouster of the Soviet-supported government of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>. `` We want to make it so expensive that people leave <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Sera </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. `` They are facing a big shortage of food.'' <PERSON> Burhanuddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabbani </PERSON>, leader of the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Jamiat-e-islami </ORGANIZATION> group, said rebel factions must develop a coordinated plan to cut all roads around <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> in order to conquer the city. `` We must have total blockage,'' he told a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> journalist last week in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. An average Afghan worker earns about 3,500 afghanis a month, now worth less than $ 10. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials estimate prices have gone up 200 percent since Jan. 1. The closure of the <LOCATION> Logar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION> has made things worse: the price of a 7-pound sack of flour in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> has risen from $ 1.72 on July 4 to $ 2.43 last week _ 27 percent of a typical worker's monthly salary. Meanwhile, the cost of one nan has jumped from 1 -LCB- cents to 3.6 cents. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> sources say that in recent weeks they have seen many <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> residents migrating north, where there are fewer rocket attacks and food is more plentiful and cheaper. `` I can say all people are facing malnutrition. All they have is one piece of bread and tea three times a day,'' said <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>, a 33-year-old academic. `` I do n't know how we survive ... If the roads are blocked, we will die of hunger.'' On a recent weekend, more than 100 trucks were lined up outside <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s main silo waiting to unload grain, but it was not for immediate consumption. The government is replenishing its grain reserves to avoid a repetition of last winter's severe shortages. This grain shipment from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was transported down the <LOCATION> Salang </LOCATION> Highway without apparent difficulty. <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Stockwell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> said the Afghan government has reported the silo now holds about 20,000 metric tons of grain, up from just under 8,000 metric tons two weeks ago. A metric ton is equivalent to 2,205 pounds or 1.1 short tons. While the silo has a capacity of 50,000 tons, the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> has said it can stockpile only about 40,000 tons for the winter, <PERSON> Stockwell </PERSON> said. That amount represents less than half the estimated 90,000 to 100,000 tons needed to get <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> through the three worst winter months, he said. It is n't clear yet where the rest will come from _ possibly the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> or the Soviets. Negotiations with the Soviets are under way in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Stockwell </PERSON> said. In the past week, the silo has been a prime target of rocket attacks. Many missed, but on one day, a rocket shattered windows and caused other minor damage. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s residents remain preoccupied with finding enough to eat. <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> said he could n't afford rice: a 7-pound sack now costs $ 4.62, a little less than half his monthly salary of $ 10.25. The biggest worry, however, is flour. `` An Afghan will be hungry unless he gets three nans every day,'' said a Western relief expert. `` This is the mainstay of the Afghan diet.''
