<PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> were running through a series of tests Saturday to make certain the shuttle's computers and control jets were ready. In addition, mission specialists <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Leestma </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> were packing up the experiments. Some of those tests were believed to be connected with the `` Star Wars'' missile defense project, while others involved determining how people can serve as military observers from space. During their mission, the five military men also reportedly monitored military tactical and strategic targets on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. The main goal of the flight was widely believed to be the deployment of a sophisticated, 10-ton spy satellite that is designed to snap highly detailed photographs over a wide area of the globe, including most of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> confirmed Wednesday that a satellite was deployed by the astronauts during their first day in orbit, but he would n't discuss its purpose.
