<HEAD>Scholars: Light and Dark Sides Are Secrets of Twain's Staying Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELMIRA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Although <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON>'s humor is a chief reason for his enduring popularity, several scholars meeting to commemorate one of the author's least humorous novels said <PERSON> Twain </PERSON>'s brooding side will also help keep him relevant to future generations `` I think people are figuring out that they ca n't some day say, ` Well, <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON>, he's out of it. He was just a mindless optimist,''' said <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Budd </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor and editor of the `` Journal of American Literature.'' `` People do know there was a darker and more irreverent side to <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Budd </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Budd </PERSON> was among about 150 literary scholars and <PERSON> Twain </PERSON> fans attending a three-day conference sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Elmira </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Twain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at Quarry Farm to mark the 100th anniversary of the publication of `` A <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> in King Arthur's Court. The conference, held Thursday, Friday and Saturday in the city where <PERSON> Twain </PERSON> is buried, showed how popular the author remains 79 years after his death. `` Only a few years ago, academic types like myself were polled on who was the greatest American writer and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitman </PERSON> came out No. 1,'' said <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina