>'' as presaging the final two troubled decades of <PERSON> Twain </PERSON>'s own life, when a series of financial and personal setbacks prompted a string of bitter, misanthropic writings. <PERSON> Budd </PERSON> referred to this stage of the author's life as the `` late, atheistic, outrageous <PERSON> Twain </PERSON>.'' Still, Crews and most other experts at the conference agreed that many passages in `` A <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION>'' exhibit the kind of homespun wit and humor <PERSON> Twain </PERSON> became famous for in `` The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn'' and other books. `` It has the makings of a classic,'' he said of `` A <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION>.'' According to <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Twain </PERSON>'s reputation has profited from the added attention the author has received from centennial celebrations of `` Huckleberry Finn'' in 1985 and `` A <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> Yankee'' this year. `` You must know the worst thing that could happen to a writer is to be forgotten,'' he said. `` No one has forgotten this guy.''
