<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUWAHATI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Battles between tribesmen and native Assamese in northeastern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> have left at least 95 people dead, witnesses and news reports said Saturday. One official said 60,000 residents had fled. The warring sides fought with spears, bows and arrows, and homemade guns, said a witness to the clashes at <LOCATION> Gohpur </LOCATION>. `` It was like an ancient war,'' said <PERSON> Dibya </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalita </PERSON>, who fled to <LOCATION> Guwahati </LOCATION> to escape the violence. Gohpur is 112 miles northeast of this capital city of <LOCATION> Assam </LOCATION> state. The Bodo tribesmen, who are of Mongol origin, are campaigning for a separate homeland in <LOCATION> Assam </LOCATION>, a remote state bordering <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> news agency said Saturday that 95 bodies have been found in the area. It said the clashes had raged over the past four days. Officials reported five deaths, but their count was believed to be much too low. The <LOCATION> Assam </LOCATION> director-general of police, S.V. <PERSON> Subramanium </PERSON>, confirmed reports of the battles but said he was awaiting details. The Assamese backlash at <LOCATION> Gohpur </LOCATION> started after 10 Assamese were burnt to death in a neighboring area. Bodo militants were blamed for the deaths. Hundreds of Bodo homes in 20 villages were set on fire, forcing residents to flee to neighboring <LOCATION> Arunachal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pradesh </LOCATION> state. A state government spokesman in the state capital, <LOCATION> Itanagar </LOCATION>, said 60,000 Bodos had crossed the state border since Wednesday. `` We are trying to provide them with shelter, but we fear more will come over,'' one official said by telephone from <LOCATION> Guwahati </LOCATION>. The official spoke on condition of anonymity. The Bodos, mostly far