ngitis, she said: `` I was somewhat astounded and not a little distressed that some had interpreted my remarks yesterday as being anti-military _ anti-our men and women in the military. Nothing could be further from the truth. We all believe that ... when the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> armed forces come to the rescue, they have no peer.'' <PERSON> Bloyer </PERSON> said that while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities have permission to operate in the skies over <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, the main search effort will continue to be focused inside <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> for the time being. `` Certainly it is possible the airplane proceeded into <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, and we will be exploring that in due course,'' he said. Until now, he said, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> planes have used `` techniques that would give a 50 percent probability of detection,'' in the primary search area. `` We're changing now to a much slower and deliberate mode, which should give us n 80-90 percent capability of detection,'' he explained. The four helicopters, flown in from <ORGANIZATION> Eglin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, are equipped with infrared devices and crews trained in night vision, but regular night flights likely wo n't begin until Monday, weather allowing, when relief crews are available, he said. As it is, the choppers are flying throughout the daylight hours, with mid-air refueling from the HC-130s, he said. Earlier in the week, hopes were raised that either of the two signals monitored via satellite had come from the plane's emergency beacon. But <PERSON> Bloyer </PERSON> explained that the only ground station able to monitor the satellite data as it passed over <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> is in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, so far away that `` it's on the very fringes of the ability'' to decipher the signal correctly. Sophisticated electronic gear on lower-flying <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> planes found no signals at the two locations, and, moreover, no evidence was found in either area by thousand of Ethiopian troops which combed them on oot, he said. <PERSON> Bloyer </PERSON> noted, however, that the plane's emergency beacon would begin to deteriorate after 72 hours, and any `` usable signal'' likely would disappear in a week as the transmitter's batteries wore down.
