<SECOND>AM-Legislators-Wrapup,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Legislators Grapple With Issues On Local Horizon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State legislatures are under pressure to act on a variety of issues, including abortion, lawmakers were told during a national convention. The 5,000 delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislatures </ORGANIZATION> got the grim word from panelists and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials in dozens of sessions at the six-day meeting, which ended Friday. Increased spending is the prescription for most of the ills, but the states' economic future is clouded by large trade and federal budget deficits, said <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunez </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> president pro tempore and president of the <ORGANIZATION> NCSL </ORGANIZATION>. Unfunded federal mandates have added billions of dollars in new responsibilities for the states in recent years, <PERSON> Nunez </PERSON> said. Federal welfare reform and changes in catastrophic health care and nursing home legislation will also raise state costs, he said. A survey by <ORGANIZATION> NCSL </ORGANIZATION> staff showed that education makes up more than 50 percent of state budgets nationwide. The overall increase in spending was 7.2 percent, up from 6.6 percent a year ago. Spending on corrections rose 14.1 percent while the increase in Medicaid costs was 10.4 percent. `` The greatest concentration of fiscal problems this year was in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> states and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, places that just two years ago were faring better than most states,'' said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NCSL </ORGANIZATION> president-elect and minority leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA