<HEAD>Lebanese Shiites Commemorate Holy Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphotos BEI5,6</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NABATIYEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of Shiite Moslems in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> commemorated the holy day of Ashura Saturday with many striking their heads with the flat edge of their swords or chains until they drew blood. Ashura, marking the death in battle of <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> saint <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> in A.D. 680, is the holiest day of the year for the world's 100 million Shiite Moslems. Scores of white-robed Shiites, bleeding from head wounds and chanting religious verses, led a procession through <LOCATION> Nabatiyeh </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, a Moslem country with fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> leaders, will commemorate Ashura Sunday. Ashura is derived from the Arabic word for the number 10. It refers to the first 10 days of the first month of the Islamic lunar calendar, <LOCATION> Muharram </LOCATION>, culminating in the tenth day, the day of <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s death. The division of Islam into <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> and Sunni groups developed after the death in 632 of <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, the founder of the faith. <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>'s closest followers determined that his companion, <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakr </PERSON>, be declared the next leader of Islam. A minority of Moslems challenged the dicision and argued that the leadership should be dynastic and should therefore have gone to <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, the son-in-law and cousin of <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, who had no sons. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> did become leader but after his death in 661, a dynasty known as the Ummayids and based in <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> declared it was the ruler of Islam. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, the son of <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, challenged the Ummayid rule and the Ummayids representing the mainstream Sunnis sought to crush <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s movement. In 680, the Ummayid forces surrounded <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> and his followers and killed them in a battle at <LOCATION> Kerbala </LOCATION>, about 100 miles south of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> in modern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. But the victory did not crush the Shiites and <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s death added an element of passion to <LOCATION> Shiism </LOCATION>, which venerates martyrdom. Shiites follow the same major rules and rites as the Sunni Moslem majority of about 800 million, including five prayers a day, the pilgrimage to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, and fasting in the holy month of <LOCATION> Ramadan </LOCATION>.
