gal, the newspaper said. Republican consultants, developers and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> secured favors from <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> by appealing to the political loyalties of <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> managers, the Times said. Democratic representatives also approached <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials for grants and subsidies, but more often they took advantage of their majority in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by imposing their wishes on housing appropriations bills, the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said.
