<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of Poles stopped work for an hour in a Solidarity-organized strike, while the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> ambassador met with <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leaders and officials in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> spoke against upheaval in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. It was the first Soviet government comment on the parliamentary maneuvering in which Solidarity is trying to form a non-Communist government to lead the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s largest <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc ally. The independent Solidarity trade union movement staged the strike in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> province to demand more pay and an end to <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> influence on management. Soviet Ambassador <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Brovikov </PERSON> held an unusual series of meetings in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> on Friday, including sessions with the chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The parties traditionally have been allied with the Communists, but Solidarity is courting them to form a government.
