<FIRST>a a BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv12-13   08-12 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 12-13,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Aug 12-13</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wall Street's Summer Not So Lazy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There's not much complaining going on about the `` summer doldrums'' on Wall Street this year. Or if there is, it's hard to hear it above the din of record or near-record highs in stock prices and increasingly optimistic appraisals of the state of the nation's economy. Things are even looking a little brighter for the securities industry, one of the few sectors of the economy that felt severe ill effects from the crash of 1987. In the last few weeks just about all the major stock-market indicators have reached new peaks, surpassing the highs they set two years ago before stock prices collapsed. The laggard Dow Jones average of 30 industrials nearly made it to new high ground as well in the past week, before afternoon selling on Friday turned it back. Stock investors could hardly fault the news background, which showed a 0.4 percent decline in the producer price index and a 0.9 percent increase in retail sales for July. Those government figures suggested more strength in the consumer economy, and at the same time less upward pressure on inflation, than analysts had generally expected. Indeed, most of the evidence lately has tended to dispel fears of an impending economic slump of major proportions. `` That possibility looks extremely remote,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The economy is decelerating gradually, not rapidly.'' `` ` Soft landing' is still the best bet,'' observed <PERSON> Maury </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, economist at <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts say Wall Street's fortunes have benefited in particular from signs since late spring that individual investors, slow to heal from the wounds of the'87 crash, have at least been returning in significant numbers `` Retail activity is at its best level since the crash,'' observed <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckenfelder </PERSON>, who follows the brokerage industry for the firm of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's early, and a severe market downturn could nip it in the bud, but it looks as though the individual is coming back to the stock and bond markets.'' At the close of business on Friday, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials stood at 2,683.99, up 30.54 from the week before but still shy of the closing high of 2,722.42 it set on Aug. 25, 1987. Other readings for the week showed the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite index up .63 at 192.27; the <ORGANIZATION> NASDAQ </ORGANIZATION> composite index for the over-the-counter market up 5.06 at 462.48, and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> market value index up 4.54 at 380.64. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> averaged 200.81 million shares a day, up from 182.43 million the week before and the heaviest total this year. The pace of activity belied August's one-time image as the slowest period of the year on the Street _ a pattern that has been fading for years as investing institutions have come to play a bigger and bigger part in the markets. Individuals still carry a lot of weight, however _ if not through direct purchases and sales of stock, then through moving their money in and out of mutual funds that in turn invest it in the stock market. `` The public has finally shifted to the buy side on stock mutual funds for the first time since the crash,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Zweig </PERSON> in a recent edition of his advisory The Zweig Forecast. `` If the public comes back here, it could be a big plus.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Aug. 12-13</NOTE>
