<HEAD>The Reluctant Dow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They're ready to start the celebration here on Wall Street, but the guest of honor still has n't shown up. The missing party in question is the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, one of the few widely recognized measures of stock price trends that has n't reached a record high this summer. f it does n't put in an appearance before long, some would-be revelers worry, the hors d'oeuvres might wilt and the punch might go flat. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500-stock composite index, the benchmark against which most professional investors gauge their results, surpassed its high from the summer of 1987 a couple of weeks ago. The separate indicators for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and American Stock Exchanges and the over-the-counter market all have lately topped their pre-crash peaks. So have measures of mutual-fund performance, which matter especially to the great majority of individual investors. So, too, has the Dow's sister average that tracks transportation stocks. But official certification that the stock market has fully recovered from the crash that occurred in August, September and October of'87 has been left to await a new high in the Dow. As close as it came last Thursday and Friday, the average's Aug. 25, 1987 close of 2,722.42 still stood as the record when the weekend arrived. The average fell 28.64 points Friday to finish the week at 2,683.99. By what right has this stubborn creature held up the festivities? Well, analysts say, it has the privileges of seniority if nothing else. `` The Dow Jones industrial average is the granddaddy of all the market indices,'' noted analysts at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in a recent commentary on the situation. `` Developed at the end of the last century, it was designed to be easy to calculate in those days of inkwells and green eyeshades. Most of the newer market indices are broader in scope and track many more individual issues.'' To be fair about it, the average has been modernized over the past decade or so to include such stalwart companies of the 1980s as <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> among its 30 components. Still, analysts say, the average remains dominated by `` smokestack'' industrial companies whose stocks have lagged of late because of intensified international competition and, most recently, worries about a possible recession in this country. `` The <ORGANIZATION> DJIA </ORGANIZATION> being a laggard is somewhat unusual,'' observed <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicoski </PERSON> at the brokerage firm of <ORGANIZATION> Piper </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jaffray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Hopwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in a recent commentary. `` But because of the economic-sensitive nature of many of its components, it should not be totally unexpected.'' Since the market peak two years ago, the biggest drag on the Dow average has been one of its most illustrious members, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION>, which remained last week more than $ 55 below its 1987 high of $ 174.87. Analysts say the Dow also has suffered from a special factor _ a dearth of takeover interest in most of its components, because of their size. Behemoths like <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> are more likely to be acquirers, as they have been, than acquirees. If the industrials had attracted bids the way issues in the transportation average _ <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> and so forth _ have lately, the story would have been much different. In fact, members of the industrial elite have become takeover targets in the past _ for example, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION>, from <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> in 1985. On those occasions, objections have often been raised that the Dow was overstating the market's strength.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon Aug 14</NOTE>
